    <body>
      <trans-unit id="9355" identifier="eb8bb9acd9d95cbcf6e05abf54a997aa">
        <source>Codes for letters using binary representation</source>
        <target>crwdns9355:0crwdne9355:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 1&#13;
XPath: /h1</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9356" identifier="f17e7b5da610295808d4668fae87df1b">
        <source>Key questions</source>
        <target>crwdns9356:0crwdne9356:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9357" identifier="33e8e11b70e6e34ce7b7a5a65f120341">
        <source>How many different characters can you type on a computer?</source>
        <target>crwdns9357:0crwdne9357:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9358" identifier="9e7e8ad8a7dceb9b799b55075e278c3e">
        <source>(Discussion may start at the 26 letters of the English alphabet, and then
expand to other characters on the keyboard, including capital letters,
digits and punctuation.</source>
        <target>crwdns9358:0crwdne9358:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9359" identifier="bf7fca292eb499dc54b74445a02d27b9">
        <source>Students may be aware that other languages can have thousands of
characters, and the range of characters is also expanding as emoticons
are invented!)</source>
        <target>crwdns9359:0crwdne9359:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9360" identifier="4460fd52c3ef567c91cd109657e20025">
        <source>Lesson starter</source>
        <target>crwdns9360:0crwdne9360:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9361" identifier="452c3bccc110436f288943d81755dd92">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;general&quot; title=&quot;Notes on resources&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9361:0crwdne9361:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9362" identifier="aa54b0522633544d9e0272b7448d86d7">
        <source>There is also an online interactive version of the binary cards &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.csfieldguide.org.nz/en/interactives/binary-cards/index.html?digits=8&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;, from the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.csfieldguide.org.nz/&quot;&gt;Computer Science Field Guide&lt;/a&gt;, but it is preferable to work with physical cards.</source>
        <target>crwdns9362:0crwdne9362:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9363" identifier="3a1ae082a90b504339024ac691a2b919">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns9363:0{panel end}crwdne9363:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9364" identifier="fd56847b3b3f3962f3948f40a7b0c4d2">
        <source>Discuss how you would communicate a letter of the alphabet to someone if all
you could do is say a number between 0 and 26.</source>
        <target>crwdns9364:0crwdne9364:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9365" identifier="4c40d3f95c09944752fb37c95e5687f5">
        <source>&lt;em&gt;(Students will usually suggest using a code of 1 or a, 2 for b, and so on)&lt;/em&gt;.</source>
        <target>crwdns9365:0crwdne9365:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9366" identifier="5290f04619592b8ccd83ce2ef441a946">
        <source>Work out and write down the binary numbers using 5 bits from 0 to 26 on the
Binary to Alphabet resource, then add the letters of the alphabet.</source>
        <target>crwdns9366:0crwdne9366:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9367" identifier="f6971ae181d97b0e4dcecba61e496c49">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/col_binary_robot_boy_convo.png&quot; alt=&quot;Cartoon boy talking to robot&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9367:0crwdne9367:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9368" identifier="d34b5f41cf6613df29ff8490bd6d120a">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9368:0crwdne9368:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9369" identifier="3e09d330bbd503442451015527babc9d">
        <source>Check their binary code for three is 00011 as students commonly write
00100 as they anticipate the pattern without necessarily checking it is
correct.</source>
        <target>crwdns9369:0crwdne9369:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9370" identifier="37545cac4602e9fad2dcaccf90df1f05">
        <source>Check they are writing the binary code in the correct order with the
least significant value on the right - for example some will start with
one as 10000 instead of 00001.</source>
        <target>crwdns9370:0crwdne9370:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9371" identifier="ae74b2a0d6ece35a3918065d164f30e2">
        <source>Identify the students who are demonstrating one or all of these
computational thinking attributes; being very systematic, have everything
lined up exactly, are the first to recognise the pattern and don’t need
the cards any more.</source>
        <target>crwdns9371:0crwdne9371:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9372" identifier="f4709b2d51f12d22dbaa1251074182d5">
        <source>Check that all students can describe back to you how to calculate the
number they are up to.
This will identify those who are guessing the pattern.</source>
        <target>crwdns9372:0crwdne9372:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9373" identifier="38c7b1f885ba0b556356df5921b45fa4">
        <source>Note that if your local alphabet is slightly different (e.g. has
diacritics, macrons etc.) then you may wish to adapt the code to
match the common characters; this issue is also considered below.</source>
        <target>crwdns9373:0crwdne9373:0</target>
        <note>Context: List Item&#13;
XPath: /ul[2]/li[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9374" identifier="76814e424523d7b9391aeb58dbd9452d">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns9374:0{panel end}crwdne9374:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[8]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9375" identifier="ea08f2f76d1ef4a9f87b3ba4c0221b4a">
        <source>Lesson activities</source>
        <target>crwdns9375:0crwdne9375:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[3]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9376" identifier="c508ee87f19eacf45e2e8f5e3e99052e">
        <source>Using the table that students have created above, give them a message to
decode, such as your name or the name of a book
author (e.g. 00001 00010 00010 11001 for ABBY).</source>
        <target>crwdns9376:0crwdne9376:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[9]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9377" identifier="b2c172f4ab132eb5cdf499a3b174d55b">
        <source>Now get students to write and communicate their own messages.
Remind them that they can write the zeroes and ones using any symbols, such
as ticks and crosses.</source>
        <target>crwdns9377:0crwdne9377:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[10]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9378" identifier="66a19a285d1fcad49ec1964d63a6ed53">
        <source>Consider unusual representations; for example, each bit could be communicated
with a sound that is either high pitched or low pitched.</source>
        <target>crwdns9378:0crwdne9378:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9379" identifier="9951c3f893b87fcae63d3cb06048a2ff">
        <source>Or the 5-bit number could be represented by holding up the five fingers on
one hand, one finger corresponding to each bit.</source>
        <target>crwdns9379:0crwdne9379:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[11]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9380" identifier="02601fa1ba44c36de24c288ddc66afad">
        <source>Adding more characters</source>
        <target>crwdns9380:0crwdne9380:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9381" identifier="50d07925ee8381bf5df818dd494aa1a6">
        <source>Some languages have slightly more or fewer characters, which might include
those with diacritic marks.</source>
        <target>crwdns9381:0crwdne9381:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9382" identifier="1c0fd60f00ba9042fea80ad7e7c0715a">
        <source>If students consider an alphabet with more than 32 characters, then 5 bits
won't be sufficient.</source>
        <target>crwdns9382:0crwdne9382:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9383" identifier="44a4df355997a1b7615070a1cf733e92">
        <source>Also, students may have realised that a code is needed for a space
(0 is a good choice for that), so 5 bits only covers 31 alphabet
characters.</source>
        <target>crwdns9383:0crwdne9383:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[12]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9384" identifier="0b1eafd83f4c7f82e4b6856f8529ebb9">
        <source>Have the students design a system that can handle a few extra characters such
as diacritics.
(This can usually be done by allocating larger numbers, such as 27 to 31, to
the other characters).</source>
        <target>crwdns9384:0crwdne9384:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[13]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9385" identifier="c205140a582f0226d8d68ca4aec91ef1">
        <source>A typical English language computer keyboard has about 100 characters
(which includes capital and lowercase letters, punctuation, digits, and
special symbols).</source>
        <target>crwdns9385:0crwdne9385:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9386" identifier="d7685fdd76bc399647aefcbe3f19d421">
        <source>How many bits are needed to give a unique number to every character
on the keyboard?</source>
        <target>crwdns9386:0crwdne9386:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9387" identifier="df995fb86be63ec2277551fd76bd6aac">
        <source>(Typically 7 bits will been enough since it provides 128 different codes).</source>
        <target>crwdns9387:0crwdne9387:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[14]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9388" identifier="cfb5a79f6c528184f6f06e16f545b2de">
        <source>Now have students consider larger alphabets.
How many bits are needed if you want a number for each of 50,000 Chinese
characters?
(16 bits allows for up to 65,536 different representations).</source>
        <target>crwdns9388:0crwdne9388:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[15]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9389" identifier="791041f240926847efae717816ecac3c">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9389:0crwdne9389:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[16]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9390" identifier="109008770758681fa68563678ab22a25">
        <source>It may be a surprise that only 16 bits is needed for tens of thousands of
characters.</source>
        <target>crwdns9390:0crwdne9390:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9391" identifier="f847eb5ff93be8ea8c88d863c261f230">
        <source>This is because each bit doubles the range, so you don't need to add many
bits to cover a large alphabet.</source>
        <target>crwdns9391:0crwdne9391:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9392" identifier="7a989f3a8e878d4f33b96d8ad9931eaa">
        <source>This is an important property of binary representation that students should
become familiar with.</source>
        <target>crwdns9392:0crwdne9392:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9393" identifier="127a98d13ea2273a464ad5925a0625d4">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns9393:0{panel end}crwdne9393:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9394" identifier="285272f1e1d5a0ca7ef54762de986cff">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;math&quot; title=&quot;Mathematical links&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9394:0crwdne9394:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9395" identifier="a3a85bb55f2c2d8992a9bf9868dd8695">
        <source>The rapid increase in the number of different values that can be represented
as bits are added is &lt;em&gt;exponential&lt;/em&gt; growth i.e. it doubles with each extra bit.</source>
        <target>crwdns9395:0crwdne9395:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9396" identifier="422f4fe6f73f1024636c813e02704898">
        <source>After doubling 16 times we can represent 65,536 different values, and 20 bits
can represent over a million different values.</source>
        <target>crwdns9396:0crwdne9396:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9397" identifier="e96a139709d29736951f6bf9c6b27d94">
        <source>Exponential growth is sometimes illustrated with folding paper in half, and
half again.</source>
        <target>crwdns9397:0crwdne9397:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9398" identifier="4ce865a05ade77bf6c4ee274a04d2802">
        <source>After these two folds, it is 4 sheets thick, and one more fold is 8 sheets
thick.</source>
        <target>crwdns9398:0crwdne9398:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9399" identifier="cef70a23a359245b13b0f08a0cbfd58d">
        <source>16 folds will be 65,536 sheets thick!</source>
        <target>crwdns9399:0crwdne9399:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9400" identifier="04c8b8657593e7342f8ea732a1ce4438">
        <source>In fact, around 6 or 7 folds is already impossibly thick, even with a large
sheet of paper.</source>
        <target>crwdns9400:0crwdne9400:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9401" identifier="3e36fd398241fc175b47e35cddcdc6f1">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns9401:0{panel end}crwdne9401:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9402" identifier="f1503269d8ab787743fcf4118c17a17e">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;teaching&quot; title=&quot;Teaching observations&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns9402:0crwdne9402:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[22]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9403" identifier="630390069e447a0ae5e07090b71075d7">
        <source>Using a 5-bit code for an alphabet goes back to at least 1870 (the &quot;Baudot&quot;
code); many different number to letter correspondences have been used over the
years to represent alphabets, but one that was common for some time is &quot;ASCII&quot;,
which used 7 bits and therefore could represent over 100 different characters.</source>
        <target>crwdns9403:0crwdne9403:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9404" identifier="497f6f8d94e1aceb240cc8a8eb0fc429">
        <source>These days &quot;Unicode&quot; is common, which can represent over 100,000 different
characters.</source>
        <target>crwdns9404:0crwdne9404:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9405" identifier="04eaf545c98890bf117218d7864e7edf">
        <source>Nevertheless, each of these codes, including Unicode, still contain elements
of the simple code used in this lesson (A is 1, B is 2...).</source>
        <target>crwdns9405:0crwdne9405:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="9406" identifier="c85293aba7f31f7e2c8188e9d9bd289b">
        <source>For example, the ASCII code for &quot;A&quot; is 65 and &quot;B&quot; is 66 etc.; if you work
out the binary representations of these, and just keep the right-most 5 bits,
you've got the code that we've been using above.</source>
        <target>crwdns9406:0crwdne9406:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
